{"add":{"doc":{"id":"2f1154a58974cc441b798272917b0c83cf44b0bf6c884fd9f6e0307edd54113b","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/VectorField.svg/250px-VectorField.svg.png","previous":[],"after":["In vector calculus, a vector field is an assignment of a vector to each point in a subset of space.[1] A vector field in the plane, for instance, can be visualized as a collection of arrows with a given magnitude and direction each attached to a point in the plane. Vector fields are often used to model, for example, the speed and direction of a moving fluid throughout space, or the strength and direction of some force, such as the magnetic or gravitational force, as it changes from point to point."]}}}